The push-pull approach is a methodology used in psychology to investigate the underlying wants and motives that shape behavior. It is predicated on the notion that some intrinsic human motives or drives, such the need for food or safety, have developed throughout the course of human evolution. By assessing how rapidly a person is willing to push or pull a joystick in response to various stimuli, such as pictures of food or images of danger, the push/pull method is used to evaluate these wants. The experimental word "cake" should elicit a higher positive emotional response and a stronger urge to approach if users press it with the joystick quicker than the neutral term "window." It implies that the term "cake" is connected to an ideal result, like pleasure or contentment. The response of pushing more quickly in the direction of the word "cake" shows that it has a greater value in terms of the person's needs and desires. 